# Integration Test Conventions

## Every new test fixture

- Inherit from `IntegrationTestBase` (provides `Factory`, `NewUser()`, and `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]`)
- Place in `Tests/<FeatureArea>/` mirroring the request folder structure (`Tests/League/`, `Tests/LeagueManager/`, `Tests/Royale/`, etc.)
- One `[TestFixture]` class per feature area

## League scenario tests

League multi-step fixtures use `LeagueFixture` + `LeagueFixtureBuilder` (see `Helpers/LeagueFixture.cs`):

```
Tests/League/
  Setup/              ← smoke + member management (no draft)
  Draft/
    LeagueDraftTestBase.cs
    Scenarios/        ← full draft completion
    EdgeCases/        ← mid-draft error tests
  Actions/            ← post-draft bid/drop/eligibility
```

- `LeagueFixtureBuilder.CreateAndStartDraftAsync(Factory, scenario, NewUser)` — league ready at draft start
- `LeagueFixtureBuilder.CreateLeagueWithMembersAsync(...)` — stops before `StartDraft` (member tests)
- Use `League.Manager` for the manager session; use `League.Publishers` indexed by draft order for player publishers (no fixed index for the manager)
- `League.CapturePublisherState(snapshot)` — copy post-draft budget/drop counts onto `TestPublisher` instances
- `LeaguePickupActions.PlaceBidAsync` / `PlaceDropAsync` — shared bid/drop placement in action fixtures
- Scenario-specific game IDs stay in a private record on the fixture class
- Admin/clock calls use `ApiSession.Admin` and `ActionRunner` directly — no wrapper helpers
- Dispose the fixture in `[OneTimeTearDown]`: `await League.DisposeAsync()`

For full-draft shared assertions, inherit `LeagueDraftTestBase` in `Tests/League/Draft/`.

## Test data

- Always use `NewUser()` for user credentials — never hardcode emails or display names
- Build state through the API; never insert directly into the DB

## Typed clients (NSwag-generated)

`ApiSession` exposes pre-wired typed client properties, one per controller:

```
session.Royale         → RoyaleClient
session.RoyaleGroup    → RoyaleGroupClient
session.League         → LeagueClient
session.LeagueManager  → LeagueManagerClient
session.Account        → AccountClient
session.Game           → GameClient
session.Admin          → AdminClient
session.General        → GeneralClient
session.CombinedData   → CombinedDataClient
session.Conference     → ConferenceClient
session.FactChecker    → FactCheckerClient
session.ActionRunner   → ActionRunnerClient
```

All request and response types come from the `FantasyCritic.ApiClient` namespace (generated by NSwag — `using FantasyCritic.ApiClient;`). Do **not** import types from `FantasyCritic.Web.Models.Requests.*` or `FantasyCritic.Lib.SharedSerialization.API.*` in test files.

Never use raw URL strings, anonymous objects, or `JObject` — compile-time breakage on contract changes is the goal.

## Keeping the generated client typed

NSwag generates a typed return value only when the controller action declares an explicit success response type. When a generated client method returns `Task` (void) instead of `Task<T>`, the fix is almost always to add a `[ProducesResponseType]` attribute to the controller action:

```csharp
// Before — NSwag generates Task (void), tests can't use the return value
[HttpPost]
public async Task<IActionResult> CreateThing([FromBody] CreateThingRequest request) { ... }

// After — NSwag generates Task<ThingViewModel>, tests can assert on the result
[HttpPost]
[ProducesResponseType<ThingViewModel>(StatusCodes.Status200OK)]
public async Task<IActionResult> CreateThing([FromBody] CreateThingRequest request) { ... }
```

**Rule:** Always prefer adding a `[ProducesResponseType]` annotation over accepting an untyped client method. If making the response typed requires anything more than adding the attribute (e.g., restructuring the return path), flag it and decide together.

Common cases that need annotations:
- `IActionResult` return types with a meaningful body (the annotation tells NSwag what the body is)
- `CreatedAtAction` / `CreatedAtRoute` responses (NSwag needs `[ProducesResponseType<T>(Status201Created)]` to generate `Task<T>`)
- Actions that return different types on different status codes

## Regenerating the API client

Run this after any API change before running tests:

```powershell
dotnet build src/FantasyCritic.Web/FantasyCritic.Web.csproj
scripts/Regenerate-ApiClient.ps1
dotnet build
```

## Running

- MySQL Docker container must be up first: `docker compose -f infrastructure/docker-compose-mysql.yaml up -d`
- Run with `-c Release` when the dev web server is running (dev server holds Debug DLL locks)

```powershell
dotnet test src/FantasyCritic.IntegrationTests/FantasyCritic.IntegrationTests.csproj -c Release
```

## No cleanup

Tests use GUID-based unique identifiers; they never collide across runs and require no teardown.
